# Class: <https://w3id.org/pmd/AUTOMATCE_0000002> (raw material role)

Class: <https://w3id.org/pmd/AUTOMATCE_0000002>

  Annotations:
    rdfs:comment 
      "This role is realized when the material enters the supply chain or the hopper of a processing machine."@en,
    rdfs:label 
      "raw material role"@en,
    skos:definition 
      "A role borne by a material entity when it functions as an input to a manufacturing process prior to transformation or processing."@en,
    skos:example 
      "Plastic granules sitting in a silo waiting to be fed into an extruder bear this role."@en

  SubClassOf:
    obo:BFO_0000023

    
# Class: <https://w3id.org/pmd/AUTOMATCE_0000003> (additive role)

Class: <https://w3id.org/pmd/AUTOMATCE_0000003>

  Annotations:
    rdfs:comment
      "Additives are distinct from fillers (which bulk up volume) and the matrix. They perform specific chemical or physical modifications."@en,
    rdfs:label
      "additive role"@en,
    skos:definition
      "A role borne by a substance intentionally added in relatively small amounts to modify the processing characteristics, performance properties, or cost of a base material."@en,
    skos:example
      "UV stabilizers added to dashboard polymers to prevent sun damage; Plasticizers added to PVC."@en

  SubClassOf:
    obo:BFO_0000023


# Class: <https://w3id.org/pmd/AUTOMATCE_0000004> (organic colorant)

Class: <https://w3id.org/pmd/AUTOMATCE_0000004>

  Annotations:
    rdfs:comment
      "Organic colorants (dyes) offer high color strength and brightness but may have lower thermal stability than pigments."@en,
    rdfs:label
      "organic colorant"@en,
    skos:definition
      "A complex organic chemical compound used to impart color, typically soluble in the medium."@en,
    skos:example
      "Azo dyes used in interior textile coloring."@en

  SubClassOf:
    pmd:PMD_0000868

  DisjointWith:
    <https://w3id.org/pmd/AUTOMATCE_0000005>


# Class: <https://w3id.org/pmd/AUTOMATCE_0000005> (inorganic colorant)

Class: <https://w3id.org/pmd/AUTOMATCE_0000005>

  Annotations:
    rdfs:comment
      "Inorganic colorants (pigments) are generally insoluble and provide opacity and high heat stability."@en,
    rdfs:label
      "inorganic colorant"@en,
    skos:definition
      "A mineral-based chemical compound, usually an oxide or sulfide, used to impart color."@en,
    skos:example
      "Titanium dioxide (white) used in car paints."@en

  SubClassOf:
    pmd:PMD_0000002


# Class: <https://w3id.org/pmd/AUTOMATCE_0000006> (colorant role)

Class: <https://w3id.org/pmd/AUTOMATCE_0000006>

  Annotations:
    rdfs:comment
      "This role can be borne by organic dyes or inorganic pigments."@en,
    rdfs:label
      "colorant role"@en,
    skos:definition
      "A role borne by an additive substance when its primary function is to impart color to a material."@en,
    skos:example
      "Carbon black acting as a pigment to turn a tire black."@en

  SubClassOf:
    <https://w3id.org/pmd/AUTOMATCE_0000003>


# Class: <https://w3id.org/pmd/AUTOMATCE_0000008> (color)

Class: <https://w3id.org/pmd/AUTOMATCE_0000008>

  Annotations:
    rdfs:comment
      "Can be defined descriptively (Red) or metrologically (L*a*b* coordinates)."@en,
    rdfs:label
      "color"@en,
    skos:definition
      "The quality of an object or substance with respect to light reflected by the object, usually determined visually by measurement of hue, saturation, and brightness."@en,
    skos:example
      "The 'Piano Black' finish on a B-pillar trim."@en

  SubClassOf:
    pmd:PMD_0020131


# Class: <https://w3id.org/pmd/AUTOMATCE_0000009> (polyamide)

Class: <https://w3id.org/pmd/AUTOMATCE_0000009>

  Annotations:
    rdfs:comment
      "Polyamides are semi-crystalline polymers known for good thermal and chemical resistance."@en,
    rdfs:label
      "polyamide"@en,
    skos:definition
      "A polymer containing repeating amide (-CONH-) linkages in the polymer backbone."@en,
    skos:example
      "Nylon 6, Nylon 12, Nylon 66."@en,
    pmd:PMD_0050117
      "PA"

  SubClassOf:
    pmd:PMD_0050004


# Class: <https://w3id.org/pmd/AUTOMATCE_0000010> (PA66)

Class: <https://w3id.org/pmd/AUTOMATCE_0000010>

  Annotations:
    rdfs:comment
      "PA66 has a higher melting point (~260°C) than PA6 but absorbs moisture which affects dimensional stability."@en,
    rdfs:label
      "PA66"@en,
    skos:definition
      "A semicrystalline thermoplastic polyamide synthesized from hexamethylenediamine and adipic acid."@en,
    skos:example
      "Material used for cylinder head covers and radiator end tanks."@en,
    pmd:PMD_0050117
      "PA66"

  SubClassOf:
    <https://w3id.org/pmd/AUTOMATCE_0000009>


# Class: <https://w3id.org/pmd/AUTOMATCE_0000011> (PA66-GF25)

Class: <https://w3id.org/pmd/AUTOMATCE_0000011>

  Annotations:
    rdfs:comment
      "The addition of 25% glass fiber significantly increases stiffness and tensile strength compared to neat PA66."@en,
    rdfs:label
      "PA66-GF25"@en,
    skos:definition
      "A composite material consisting of a Polyamide 66 matrix reinforced with 25% glass fiber by mass."@en,
    skos:example
      "Structural components in the engine bay requiring high stiffness at elevated temperatures."@en

  SubClassOf:
    pmd:PMD_0000577


# Class: <https://w3id.org/pmd/AUTOMATCE_0000012> (fiber)

Class: <https://w3id.org/pmd/AUTOMATCE_0000012>

  Annotations:
    rdfs:comment
      "In PMD logic, this is a disconnected aggregate because the individual filaments in a bundle are distinct objects."@en,
    rdfs:label
      "fiber"@en,
    skos:definition
      "A class of materials that are continuous filaments or are in discrete elongated pieces, similar to lengths of thread."@en,
    skos:example
      "Carbon fiber tow, Aramid fibers."@en

  SubClassOf:
    pmd:PMD_0000891


# Class: <https://w3id.org/pmd/AUTOMATCE_0000013> (glass fiber)

Class: <https://w3id.org/pmd/AUTOMATCE_0000013>

  Annotations:
    rdfs:comment
      "Used extensively as a reinforcement agent in polymer matrix composites."@en,
    rdfs:label
      "glass fiber"@en,
    skos:definition
      "A material consisting of numerous extremely fine fibers of glass."@en,
    skos:example
      "E-Glass used to reinforce PA66 for automotive pedals."@en,
    pmd:PMD_0050117
      "GF"

  SubClassOf:
    <https://w3id.org/pmd/AUTOMATCE_0000012>


# Class: <https://w3id.org/pmd/AUTOMATCE_0000014> (fiber material content mass fraction)

Class: <https://w3id.org/pmd/AUTOMATCE_0000014>

  Annotations:
    rdfs:comment
      "Commonly denoted as wt%. PA66-GF25 implies a value of 0.25 or 25%."@en,
    rdfs:label
      "fiber material content mass fraction"@en,
    skos:definition
      "The ratio of the mass of the fiber reinforcement to the total mass of the composite material."@en,
    skos:example
      "25% mass fraction in PA66-GF25."@en

  SubClassOf:
    pmd:PMD_0020102


# Class: <https://w3id.org/pmd/AUTOMATCE_0000015> (fiber material content volume fraction)

Class: <https://w3id.org/pmd/AUTOMATCE_0000015>

  Annotations:
    rdfs:comment
      "Volume fraction is more critical for micromechanical modeling (e.g., Rule of Mixtures) than mass fraction."@en,
    rdfs:label
      "fiber material content volume fraction"@en,
    skos:definition
      "The ratio of the volume of the fiber reinforcement to the total volume of the composite material."@en,
    skos:example
      "Approximately 14-15% volume fraction corresponds to 25% mass fraction for Glass/PA66."@en

  SubClassOf:
    pmd:PMD_0020104

# Class: <https://w3id.org/pmd/AUTOMATCE_0000023> (viscosity)

Class: <https://w3id.org/pmd/AUTOMATCE_0000023>
  Annotations:
    rdfs:comment "Critical for injection molding simulations to predict mold filling."@en,
    rdfs:label "viscosity"@en,
    skos:definition "A measure of a fluid's resistance to flow."@en,
    skos:example "The melt viscosity of polypropylene at 230°C."@en
  SubClassOf:
    pmd:PMD_0020131

# Class: <https://w3id.org/pmd/AUTOMATCE_0000025> (shear viscosity)

Class: <https://w3id.org/pmd/AUTOMATCE_0000025>
  Annotations:
    rdfs:comment "Polymers are non-Newtonian; their shear viscosity decreases as shear rate increases (shear thinning)."@en,
    rdfs:label "shear viscosity"@en,
    skos:definition "The viscosity of a fluid when subjected to shear stress; defined as the ratio of shear stress to shear rate."@en,
    skos:example "Viscosity curve data required for Moldflow simulation."@en
  SubClassOf:
    pmd:PMD_0020131


# Class: <https://w3id.org/pmd/AUTOMATCE_0000026> (glass transition temperature)

Class: <https://w3id.org/pmd/AUTOMATCE_0000026>
  Annotations:
    rdfs:comment "Below Tg, the amorphous phase is frozen; above Tg, polymer chains have mobility."@en,
    rdfs:label "glass transition temperature"@en,
    skos:definition "The temperature range where a polymer material transitions from a hard, glassy material to a soft, rubbery material."@en,
    skos:example "Tg of approx. 50°C for dry PA66."@en,
    pmd:PMD_0050117 "Tg"
  SubClassOf:
    pmd:PMD_0000882


# Class: <https://w3id.org/pmd/AUTOMATCE_0000027> (coefficient of linear thermal expansion)

Class: <https://w3id.org/pmd/AUTOMATCE_0000027>
  Annotations:
    rdfs:comment "Crucial for calculating gap and flush in automotive assembly where different materials (steel vs plastic) meet."@en,
    rdfs:label "coefficient of linear thermal expansion"@en,
    skos:definition "The fractional change in length per degree of temperature change."@en,
    skos:example "CLTE is distinct in flow-direction vs cross-flow direction for fiber reinforced parts."@en,
    pmd:PMD_0050117 "CLTE"
  SubClassOf:
    pmd:PMD_0000981


# Class: <https://w3id.org/pmd/AUTOMATCE_0000028> (specific heat capacity)

Class: <https://w3id.org/pmd/AUTOMATCE_0000028>
  Annotations:
    rdfs:comment "Used to calculate cooling times in injection molding."@en,
    rdfs:label "specific heat capacity"@en,
    skos:definition "The amount of heat energy required to raise the temperature of a substance per unit of mass."@en,
    skos:example "1700 J/(kg·K) for Polypropylene."@en,
    pmd:PMD_0050117 "Cp"
  SubClassOf:
    pmd:PMD_0000981


# Class: <https://w3id.org/pmd/AUTOMATCE_0000032> (humidity)

Class: <https://w3id.org/pmd/AUTOMATCE_0000032>
  Annotations:
    rdfs:comment "Crucial for PA66 as it absorbs moisture, changing its mechanical properties (conditioning)."@en,
    rdfs:label "humidity"@en,
    skos:definition "The concentration of water vapor present in the air or environment surrounding a material."@en,
    skos:example "50% Relative Humidity (standard conditioning atmosphere)."@en
  SubClassOf:
    pmd:PMD_0020131


